<font color="#FF0000">REACTIONS</font><br>
<tt>Sun Oct 26 14:28:26 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
Tom, <br>
   You talked about our return. Instead of flying directly to the west coast on a freedom bird, I took a flight to Japan for a week vacation.  Flew to New York where my family lived for another week before exiting for another tour of duty in Germany.  My mother or father, can't remember which, asked what it had been like in Vietnam.  I started to try and formulate an answer and I know I started to tear up.  There were things I could have said but didn't know where to start.  I am guessing years later that my wet eyes signalled  to my parents that it was something they shouldn't ask about.  The results were that we have never talked about it again, and no one else in the family ever asked either. I forgot for years that they even asked once and was mad at them for not caring and my mother who saves every letter and birthday card for not saving a single letter I wrote from Vietnam.<br><br>
   When the men weren't accepted, or honored.... by default neither were the women. While I was with the military hospital services it wasn't a problem.  Having served in a combat area and survived had a status and respect, you knew of war.  When I left the Red Cross and started working in a civilian atmosphere the response was very different.  Civilians at least could understand the draft and a man going to war.  They couln't understand a woman doing such a thing.  I saw many a blank stare.  Ultimately, I wrote Vietnam out of my resume and tried to wipe it from my mind.  Denial worked pretty good for years.  Stayed away from anything having to do with Vietnam until 1993 and the dedication of the women's memorial at the Wall.  With the Gulf War the protective denial started to come apart at the seams.  I was never literally in a paddy dike but figuratively I think it could be said I have been in one for years and didn't even know it. ( I am guessing that the paddy dikes were about the size of the bomb craters on three sides of our hospital compound.  Just deep enough to lie down flat in and not stick your head up without putting it in danger.  Is that what you are talking about?)<br><br>
You said &quot; Reactions on this site to what &quot;you&quot; say, quite possibly are defense mechanisms (strange how I am learning all the lingo).  We often hurt the ones we love.&quot;  I add  &quot;and the ones who love us&quot;.  I don't know why this happens.  Self defense, or maybe anger because many of the men felt that American women let them down?  I believe that a number of the posts higher on this thread allude to some of the buried feelings relating to women and my presence may have brought them to the surface.  <br><br>
Betty<br>

